column1: Data Supplied By: National Livestock Reporting Service
Data source: National Livestock Reporting Service
Please see terms of use here: https://www.mla.com.au/general/Terms-and-conditions/data-and-information/

There were approximately 2400 export and 500 young cattle penned representing an increase of 570 head week-on-week. Another export processor rejoined the regular buyers in a generally firm market. Quality was very good in the trade and declined a little in the bullocks. The best trade cattle improved a little while most held firm. Grown steers sold firm while bullocks eased 5c to 10c/kg. Friesian manufacturing steers lifted 10c/kg while the crossbred portion remained firm. Light dairy cows eased slightly while heavy beef cows lifted 2c to 5c/kg. Heavy bulls gained 6c/kg. 

Vealers sold from 310c to 375c/kg. Yearling trade steers made between 322c and 364c/kg. Yearling heifers to the trade sold between 300c and 359c/kg. Grown steers made from 322c to 365c/kg. Bullocks sold from 328c to 370c/kg. Heavy grown heifers made between 315c and 335c/kg. 

Heavy Friesian manufacturing steers sold between 265c and 318c with the crossbred portion between 286c and 349c/kg. Most light and medium weight cows made from 210c to 288c/kg. Heavy weight cows sold mostly from 232c to 312c/kg. Heavy bulls made between 232c and 287c/kg. 

Market reporter: Brendan Fletcher.
